Content: [dscrd-hush] <1112> If a group, corporation, etc., wants to communicate securely in a decentralized manner on the blockchain, can't they just fork HUSH (since it's open-source) and do some small changes to airdrop every address 1 HUSH every hour, which will be enough to send all the necessary messages, then rent some hashing power in NiceHash and pay for the Komodo dPoW, and have a full solution for a few thousand dollars instead of paying us $1 for each hush in the future?

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> I see what your argument is, but I think the assumptions that you have are incorrect.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> JP Morgan runs Quorum, their enterprise version of Ethereum. And they dont use the Ethereum network, and they don't have to pay GAS

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> Let's say someone did fork Hush. How secure would their network be, if nobody was mining it?

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> Who would be constantly working to maintain the code?

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> How secure would they actually be? Why not just anonymously use Hush, which is already up & running and secure?

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <Crypto99> Easier to let someone else do all of the work, and just use the product.
